In another work, a microbalance sensing technique has been developed for ultrasensitive glucose detection in artificial saliva. The quartz crystal microbalance (QCM) is highly effective in biological study and measurement for its excellent sensitivity, swift response, real-time analysis capability, ease of use, and low production cost. However, it remains challenging to detect trace quantities of minor molecules such as low-concentration of glucose in saliva under physiological conditions. In this study, a QCM chip was coated with a poly(boric acid) hydrogel via UV pressing-assisted polymerization to develop a straightforward glucose detection device. The sensor responded to glucose concentrations ranging from 0 to 160 mg L⁻¹ (0 to 0.89 mM) at various pH with a linear relationship between glucose concentration and the frequency shift (ΔF) within the pH range of human saliva (pH 6.8 to 7.5). As the pH increased, the ionization of boric acid was pronounced which caused several glucose-boric acid binding consequences, resulting in an increased ΔF. This QCM sensor demonstrated an exceptional LOD (3 mg L⁻¹ or 16.7 μM at pH 7.5), which is roughly 30 times lower than that of sensors made by traditional spin coating methods [121]. Later, a noninvasive, reliable wireless patch-type glucose sensor was constructed for sweat and blood serum tests. Hyaluronate-gold nanoparticles and GOx complex (HA–AuNP/GOx) were embedded into an ultralow-power application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) chip resulting in a wireless glucose sensor with slow water evaporation at 0.11 μL min⁻¹, a quick response time of 5 s, high sensitivity at 12.37 μA·dL mg⁻¹·cm⁻², a low LOD of 0.5 mg dL⁻¹ (27.8 μM), and stable enzymatic activity for around 14 days [122]. Summarized data of mice serum and sweat's glucose sensing of this device were presented in Table 2
                        . Kownacka et al. demonstrated the effectiveness of the NovioSense glucose sensor for continuous glucose sensing in tears. The sensor was placed underneath the lower eyelid at which the inferior conjunctival fornix is located (Fig. 9
                        ). Tears are produced through a sophisticated process involving the lacrimal glands, accessory lacrimal glands, and goblet cells in the conjunctiva, triggered by various environmental factors or emotional reactions [123]. The tear film has a volume of about 6–8 μL and flows across the eye's surface at a rate of 1–2 μL min⁻¹. Tears then flow into the lacrimal canaliculi, followed by the lacrimal sac situated between the upper and lower eyelids (Fig. 9A). The device incorporates a flexible coil made of several parallel wires (electrodes) twisted together to create an amperometric cell, resembling a spring with dimensions of 15 mm in length and 1.3 mm in diameter. (Fig. 9B and 9C). The wires are constructed from stainless steel and uncoated platinum/iridium (Pt/Ir, 90/10), after that it is coated with 10-μm thickness of polyesterimide for insulation and spacing purposes. The GOx was immobilized into a hydrophilic polysaccharide-based coating (patent EP2699690B1). This sensor employs a well-established and reliable enzymatic method for detecting glucose (Fig. 9D). The NovioSense sensor demonstrates excellent linearity in a range of 0–20 mM, and it yielded high accuracy at even lower concentrations. The NovioSense sensor precisely detects glucose, over the six potential interferents at physiological concentration including ascorbic acid, urea, acetaminophen, citric acid, lactic acid, and pyruvic acid (Fig. 9E). The linear range of the sensor was optimized to achieve the highest linearity between 0.1 and 1 mM, with an R2 of 0.999 [124]. This work demonstrates a strong correlation to blood glucose values, indicating clear clinical feasibility in both animal and human studies.
